Chapter 3 — The Quantum Theory of Atoms in Molecules

3.1 The Gradient Vector Field

The electron density $\rho(\mathbf{r})$ is a scalar field. Its gradient $\nabla \rho(\mathbf{r})$ defines a vector field. Integral curves (trajectories) of this vector field are called gradient paths.

Gradient paths originate and terminate at critical points where $\nabla \rho = 0$.

3.2 Critical Points

At a critical point, the Hessian matrix of second derivatives:

H_{ij} = \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial x_i \partial x_j}

has eigenvalues $\lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \lambda_3$. Critical points are classified by the pair $(\text{rank}, \text{signature})$, where rank is the number of non-zero eigenvalues and signature is the sum of their signs.

Four types of critical points in molecules:

· (3, -3): Local maximum — nuclear critical point (NCP)
· (3, -1): Saddle with two negative, one positive — bond critical point (BCP)
· (3, +1): Saddle with one negative, two positive — ring critical point (RCP)
· (3, +3): Local minimum — cage critical point (CCP)

3.3 The Bond Critical Point

A bond exists between two atoms if and only if there is a (3, -1) critical point between their nuclei, with a bond path connecting them.

Properties of the BCP characterize the bond:

· Electron density $\rho_b = \rho(\mathbf{r}_{\text{BCP}})$: correlates with bond order
· Laplacian $\nabla^2 \rho_b = \lambda_1 + \lambda_2 + \lambda_3$:
  · $\nabla^2 \rho_b < 0$: covalent bond (charge concentration)
  · $\nabla^2 \rho_b > 0$: closed-shell interaction (ionic, hydrogen bond, van der Waals)
· Ellipticity $\epsilon = \lambda_1/\lambda_2 - 1$: measures deviation from cylindrical symmetry (π-bond character)

3.4 The Laplacian and Chemical Interpretation

The Laplacian $\nabla^2 \rho$ reveals regions of charge concentration and depletion. Negative $\nabla^2 \rho$ indicates local charge concentration; positive $\nabla^2 \rho$ indicates local charge depletion.

Valence shell charge concentrations (VSCCs) correspond to:

· Bonding pairs (along bond paths)
· Lone pairs (in non-bonding directions)

VSEPR theory is a qualitative approximation to the topology of $\nabla^2 \rho$.

3.5 Atomic Basins and Atomic Properties

The gradient paths that terminate at a nucleus define its atomic basin $\Omega_A$. Integration over the basin gives atomic properties:

· Atomic population: $N_A = \int_{\Omega_A} \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r$
· Atomic charge: $q_A = Z_A - N_A$
· Atomic dipole moment, volume, energy, etc.

This provides a rigorous, quantum-mechanical definition of "an atom in a molecule."

