Chapter 5 — Solvation and Environment

5.1 The Need for Solvation Models

Most chemistry occurs in solution or at interfaces, not in vacuum. Solvent effects can:

· Stabilize or destabilize reactants/products
· Alter reaction barriers
· Change molecular geometries
· Enable proton transfer and other mechanisms

5.2 Implicit Solvation Models

Implicit solvation treats the solvent as a polarizable dielectric continuum. The solvation free energy is:

\Delta G_{\text{solv}} = \Delta G_{\text{elec}} + \Delta G_{\text{cav}} + \Delta G_{\text{disp}} + \Delta G_{\text{rep}}

Polarizable Continuum Model (PCM): The solute occupies a cavity (usually defined by overlapping atomic spheres). The solvent is a dielectric with permittivity $\epsilon$. The electrostatic contribution comes from solving the Poisson-Boltzmann equation.

Conductor-like Screening Model (COSMO): Assumes the solvent is a perfect conductor ($\epsilon = \infty$) then scales back to finite $\epsilon$.

SMD model: Includes both electrostatic and non-electrostatic terms, parameterized for many solvents.

5.3 Explicit Solvation: QM/MM

For detailed studies, especially of enzymes, we need explicit solvent molecules. Quantum Mechanics/Molecular Mechanics (QM/MM) partitions the system:

· QM region: Active site, treated quantum mechanically (DFT)
· MM region: Rest of protein and solvent, treated with molecular mechanics (force fields)

The total Hamiltonian:

\hat{H}_{\text{total}} = \hat{H}_{\text{QM}} + \hat{H}_{\text{MM}} + \hat{H}_{\text{QM/MM}}

The coupling term includes:

· Electrostatic embedding: MM charges polarize the QM region
· van der Waals interactions: Usually treated at MM level
· Bonded interactions across the QM-MM boundary: Link atoms or frozen orbitals

5.4 When to Use Which

System Method
Small molecule in common solvent Implicit (PCM, COSMO)
Reaction mechanism in solvent Implicit + DFT
Enzyme catalysis QM/MM
Explicit solvent structure desired QM/MM with explicit solvent
Excited states in solution TD-DFT + PCM or QM/MM

