Part II — The Topology of Bonding

---

Chapter 7 — The Electron Density as a Scalar Field

7.1 Mathematical Preliminaries

The electron density $\rho(\mathbf{r})$ is a continuous, real-valued scalar field defined over all space. It possesses the following mathematical properties:

· $\rho(\mathbf{r}) > 0$ everywhere (except asymptotically at infinity)
· $\rho(\mathbf{r})$ is continuous and infinitely differentiable except at nuclei
· $\int_{\mathbb{R}^3} \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r = N$, the total number of electrons
· $\rho(\mathbf{r})$ decays exponentially as $r \to \infty$: $\rho(\mathbf{r}) \sim e^{-2\sqrt{2I}r}$, where $I$ is the ionization potential

7.2 The Gradient Vector Field

The gradient $\nabla \rho(\mathbf{r})$ defines a vector field. Its integral curves—trajectories everywhere tangent to $\nabla \rho$—are called gradient paths. Each gradient path originates at a point where $\nabla \rho = 0$ and terminates at another such point.

The set of all gradient paths partitions space into disjoint regions called basins. The boundaries between basins are separatrices—surfaces through which no gradient path passes.

7.3 Critical Points

Critical points occur where $\nabla \rho = 0$. At such points, the behavior of $\rho$ is determined by the Hessian matrix:

\mathbf{H}(\mathbf{r}) = 
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial x^2} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial x \partial y} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial x \partial z} \\
\frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial y \partial x} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial y^2} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial y \partial z} \\
\frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial z \partial x} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial z \partial y} & \frac{\partial^2 \rho}{\partial z^2}
\end{pmatrix}

The Hessian is symmetric, hence diagonalizable with real eigenvalues $\lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \lambda_3$. The rank is the number of non-zero eigenvalues; the signature is the sum of the signs of the eigenvalues.

Critical points are classified by the pair $(\text{rank}, \text{signature})$:

Type Rank Signature Eigenvalue signs Physical meaning
(3, -3) 3 -3 $(-, -, -)$ Nuclear position
(3, -1) 3 -1 $(-, -, +)$ Bond
(3, +1) 3 +1 $(-, +, +)$ Ring
(3, +3) 3 +3 $(+, +, +)$ Cage

7.4 The Topological Atoms

The basin of a (3, -3) critical point (a nucleus) is the set of all points whose gradient paths terminate at that nucleus. This defines an atom in a molecule—a region of space $\Omega_A$ with a well-defined boundary $\partial\Omega_A$ through which no gradient path crosses.

Properties of the atom are obtained by integration over its basin:

· Atomic population: $N(\Omega_A) = \int_{\Omega_A} \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r$
· Atomic charge: $q(\Omega_A) = Z_A - N(\Omega_A)$
· Atomic dipole moment: $\boldsymbol{\mu}(\Omega_A) = \int_{\Omega_A} (\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R}_A) \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r$
· Atomic volume: $V(\Omega_A) = \int_{\Omega_A} d^3r$

These quantities are rigorously defined and experimentally measurable in principle.

