Chapter 9 — The Laplacian Field

9.1 Definition and Interpretation

The Laplacian $\nabla^2 \rho(\mathbf{r})$ measures the curvature of the density at each point. It can be written as:

\nabla^2 \rho(\mathbf{r}) = \lambda_1(\mathbf{r}) + \lambda_2(\mathbf{r}) + \lambda_3(\mathbf{r})

where $\lambda_i$ are the eigenvalues of the Hessian at $\mathbf{r}$ (not just at critical points).

Physical interpretation:

· $\nabla^2 \rho < 0$: Local charge concentration (electron density higher than average surroundings)
· $\nabla^2 \rho > 0$: Local charge depletion (electron density lower than average surroundings)

9.2 Valence Shell Charge Concentrations

In atoms, the Laplacian reveals the shell structure. For a free atom, $\nabla^2 \rho$ alternates sign with radial distance:

· Negative near nucleus (K-shell concentration)
· Positive between shells (inter-shell depletion)
· Negative again (L-shell concentration)
· And so on.

In molecules, the valence shell charge concentrations (VSCCs) correspond to:

· Bonding pairs: VSCCs directed along bond paths toward the BCP
· Lone pairs: VSCCs directed away from nuclei into non-bonding regions

9.3 VSEPR Theory from the Laplacian

The Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion (VSEPR) model is a qualitative approximation to the topology of $\nabla^2 \rho$. The number and arrangement of VSCCs around a nucleus predict molecular geometry:

VSCCs Arrangement Examples
2 Linear CO$_2$, BeCl$_2$
3 Trigonal planar BH$_3$, SO$_3$
4 Tetrahedral CH$_4$, NH$_4^+$
5 Trigonal bipyramidal PCl$_5$, SF$_4$
6 Octahedral SF$_6$, ClF$_5$

Lone pairs occupy more space than bonding pairs, distorting angles. In H$_2$O, the two VSCCs corresponding to lone pairs are larger than the two corresponding to O–H bonds, compressing the H–O–H angle to 104.5° (ideal tetrahedral is 109.5°).

9.4 The Local Energy Density

The energy density $H(\mathbf{r}) = G(\mathbf{r}) + V(\mathbf{r})$ provides additional insight. At a BCP:

· $H_b < 0$: Shared interaction (covalent, polar covalent)
· $H_b > 0$: Closed-shell interaction (ionic, hydrogen bond, van der Waals)

Combined with $\nabla^2 \rho_b$, we have a complete classification:

$\nabla^2 \rho_b$ $H_b$ Bond type Examples
< 0 < 0 Covalent H$_2$, C–C, N$_2$
0 < 0 Transit (weak covalent) F$_2$, some metal-metal
0 0 Closed-shell NaCl, H-bond, vdW

---

Chapter 10 — Atomic Properties from QTAIM

10.1 Atomic Charges

The atomic charge is the most fundamental atomic property:

q(\Omega_A) = Z_A - \int_{\Omega_A} \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r

These charges differ from conventional (Mulliken, Löwdin) charges because they are based on real space rather than orbital partitioning. QTAIM charges are generally larger in magnitude but correlate well with chemical intuition:

Molecule Atom QTAIM charge Mulliken charge
NaCl Na +0.97 +0.73
NaCl Cl -0.97 -0.73
H$_2$O O -1.14 -0.67
H$_2$O H +0.57 +0.33

10.2 Atomic Dipole Moments

The dipole moment of an atom in a molecule measures the polarization of its electron density:

\boldsymbol{\mu}(\Omega_A) = \int_{\Omega_A} (\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R}_A) \rho(\mathbf{r}) \, d^3r

These atomic dipoles sum to the total molecular dipole:

\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\text{total}} = \sum_A \left[ q(\Omega_A) \mathbf{R}_A + \boldsymbol{\mu}(\Omega_A) \right]

The first term is the charge transfer contribution; the second is the atomic polarization.

10.3 Atomic Energies

The energy of an atom in a molecule can be defined via the virial theorem. The total energy is:

E = \sum_A E(\Omega_A)

where $E(\Omega_A)$ is obtained by integrating the energy density over the atomic basin. This partitioning is exact and provides insight into bonding energetics.

The binding energy between atoms A and B is:

\Delta E_{AB} = E(\Omega_A) + E(\Omega_B) - E_A^0 - E_B^0

where $E_A^0$ is the energy of the isolated atom.

