Chapter 11 — Bonding Classification from Topology

11.1 Covalent Bonds

Covalent bonds are characterized by:

· $\nabla^2 \rho_b < 0$ (charge concentration between nuclei)
· $H_b < 0$ (potential energy dominates)
· $\rho_b$ typically > 0.15 au
· Bond paths are straight or nearly straight

Examples: C–C, C–H, N–N, O–H

11.2 Ionic Bonds

Ionic bonds are characterized by:

· $\nabla^2 \rho_b > 0$ (charge depletion between ions)
· $H_b > 0$ (kinetic energy dominates)
· $\rho_b$ typically < 0.05 au
· Bond paths are straight

Examples: NaCl, MgO, LiF

11.3 Hydrogen Bonds

Hydrogen bonds X–H···Y show:

· $\nabla^2 \rho_b > 0$ (closed-shell)
· $H_b > 0$ (for weak H-bonds) or $H_b < 0$ (for strong, "low-barrier" H-bonds)
· $\rho_b$ typically 0.005–0.05 au
· Bond paths are slightly curved toward H

Correlation between H-bond energy and $\rho_b$:
E_{\text{HB}} \approx -223 \rho_b \text{ (kcal/mol)} \quad (\rho_b \text{ in au})

11.4 Van der Waals Interactions

Van der Waals complexes show:

· $\nabla^2 \rho_b > 0$
· $H_b > 0$
· $\rho_b$ very small (< 0.005 au)
· Bond paths may be highly curved

11.5 Metal-Metal Bonds

Metal-metal bonds vary widely:

· Some are covalent ($\nabla^2 \rho_b < 0$, e.g., Hg$_2^{2+}$)
· Most are intermediate ($\nabla^2 \rho_b > 0$ but $H_b < 0$)
· Characterized by low $\rho_b$ and high ellipticity

