Chapter 12 — Topological Signatures of Reactivity

12.1 The Principle of Corresponding Order

Bader's Principle of Corresponding Order states that there is a one-to-one correspondence between the topological properties of the electron density in the ground state and the features of the potential energy surface.

In particular, properties at bond critical points correlate with:

· Bond lengths (inverse correlation with $\rho_b$)
· Force constants (linear correlation with $\rho_b$)
· Bond dissociation energies (correlation with $\rho_b$ and $H_b$)

12.2 Predicting Reactivity from Ground-State Topology

The central hypothesis of this volume is that reactivity can be predicted from ground-state topology alone.

For a bond A–B that will break in a reaction, the BCP properties correlate with the activation energy:

E_a \approx \alpha \rho_b + \beta \nabla^2 \rho_b + \gamma \epsilon + \delta

The coefficients $\alpha, \beta, \gamma, \delta$ depend on reaction class. This is the basis for Investigation Module 1.

12.3 The Laplacian and Nucleophilic/Elektrophilic Sites

The Laplacian $\nabla^2 \rho$ reveals sites of electrophilic and nucleophilic attack:

· Electrophilic attack occurs at regions of charge concentration ($\nabla^2 \rho < 0$)
· Nucleophilic attack occurs at regions of charge depletion ($\nabla^2 \rho > 0$)

The electrostatic potential $V(\mathbf{r})$ also correlates with reactivity, but the Laplacian provides a purely density-based descriptor.

12.4 The Bond Path as a Reaction Coordinate

As a bond forms or breaks, the bond critical point appears, moves, and disappears. Tracking the BCP along a reaction path provides insight into bond formation/cleavage:

· At long range, no BCP exists
· At the bonding distance, a BCP appears with very low $\rho_b$ and positive $\nabla^2 \rho_b$
· As the bond shortens, $\rho_b$ increases and $\nabla^2 \rho_b$ becomes negative (for covalent bonds)
· At the equilibrium distance, BCP properties reach their characteristic values
· Further compression increases $\rho_b$ but may destabilize the system (Pauli repulsion)

---

Chapter 13 — Ring and Cage Critical Points

13.1 Ring Critical Points

A (3, +1) critical point occurs at the center of a ring of bonded atoms. At an RCP:

· $\rho$ is a minimum in the plane of the ring
· $\rho$ is a maximum perpendicular to the ring

Properties at RCPs characterize aromaticity. For benzene, the RCP has $\rho \approx 0.02$ au. The ellipticity at the RCP correlates with ring strain.

13.2 Cage Critical Points

A (3, +3) critical point occurs at the center of a cage (e.g., inside C$_{60}$). At a CCP:

· $\rho$ is a local minimum in all directions

CCPs are rare but characteristic of clathrates, fullerenes, and some zeolites.

13.3 Molecular Graphs

The set of nuclei (attractors) and bond paths (lines connecting them through BCPs) form the molecular graph. This graph has the same connectivity as the Lewis structure but is derived rigorously from the electron density.

The molecular graph changes at structural catastrophes—points where bond paths appear or disappear. These correspond to transition states and other critical geometries on the PES.

