Chapter 14 — QTAIM in Practice

14.1 Computational Implementation

QTAIM analysis requires:

1. A converged electron density from quantum chemical calculation (DFT, HF, post-HF)
2. Numerical grid for integration
3. Location of critical points by following gradient paths
4. Integration over atomic basins

Standard software: AIMAll, Multiwfn, Critic2, DGrid.

14.2 Numerical Considerations

· Integration accuracy requires careful grid selection
· Atomic basins may be large and irregular
· For periodic systems (crystals), the theory extends to the electron density in the unit cell

14.3 Experimental QTAIM

High-resolution X-ray diffraction can provide experimental electron densities. Multipole refinement models the density, and QTAIM analysis can be performed on the experimental model. This provides a direct link between theory and experiment.

