Chapter 20 — The Nudged Elastic Band Method

20.1 The Chain-of-States Concept

The Nudged Elastic Band (NEB) method represents the reaction path as a chain of $N$ images $\{\mathbf{R}_1, \mathbf{R}_2, \dots, \mathbf{R}_N\}$ between fixed endpoints $\mathbf{R}_0$ (reactants) and $\mathbf{R}_{N+1}$ (products).

20.2 Forces in NEB

Each image experiences two forces:

1. True force from the PES: $\mathbf{F}_i^{\text{true}} = -\nabla E(\mathbf{R}_i)$
2. Spring force to maintain equal spacing: $\mathbf{F}_i^{\text{spring}} = k(|\mathbf{R}_{i+1} - \mathbf{R}_i| - |\mathbf{R}_i - \mathbf{R}_{i-1}|) \hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_i$

where $\hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_i$ is the unit tangent along the band.

20.3 Nudging

The key idea of NEB is to project out components of the true force perpendicular to the band, and components of the spring force parallel to the band. The total force on image $i$ is:

\mathbf{F}_i = \mathbf{F}_i^{\text{true}} - (\mathbf{F}_i^{\text{true}} \cdot \hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_i) \hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_i + \mathbf{F}_i^{\text{spring}}

This "nudging" ensures:

· The band moves toward the minimum energy path (true force perpendicular)
· Images remain evenly spaced (spring force parallel)

20.4 Climbing Image NEB

To locate the transition state precisely, the highest energy image (say image $k$) can be made to "climb" uphill:

\mathbf{F}_k = \mathbf{F}_k^{\text{true}} - 2(\mathbf{F}_k^{\text{true}} \cdot \hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_k) \hat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}_k

This image then moves uphill along the band toward the saddle point, while other images maintain the NEB forces.

20.5 Convergence and Analysis

NEB converges when the perpendicular forces on all images are near zero. The converged band approximates the minimum energy path, and the highest image approximates the transition state.

Properties along the path can be analyzed:

· Energy profile $E(s)$
· Geometrical changes
· Bond evolution (QTAIM along the path)

