Chapter 21 — Metadynamics

21.1 Principle

Metadynamics accelerates rare events by adding repulsive Gaussian bias potentials to the PES along a set of collective variables (CVs) $s(\mathbf{R})$. The bias potential discourages revisiting previously explored regions, forcing the system to explore new conformations.

21.2 The Bias Potential

At time $t$, the bias potential is:

V_{\text{bias}}(s, t) = \sum_{t' < t} W(t') \exp\left( -\frac{|s - s(t')|^2}{2\sigma^2} \right)

where $W(t')$ is the height of the Gaussian added at time $t'$, and $\sigma$ is its width.

21.3 Well-Tempered Metadynamics

In well-tempered metadynamics, the Gaussian height decreases with simulation time:

W(t) = W_0 \exp\left( -\frac{V_{\text{bias}}(s(t), t)}{k_B \Delta T} \right)

where $\Delta T$ is a parameter. This ensures convergence to a smooth free energy surface.

21.4 Free Energy Reconstruction

As the bias potential fills the wells, the free energy $F(s)$ is given by:

F(s) = -\lim_{t \to \infty} V_{\text{bias}}(s, t) + \text{constant}

In well-tempered metadynamics, the relation is:

F(s) = -\frac{T + \Delta T}{\Delta T} \lim_{t \to \infty} V_{\text{bias}}(s, t)

21.5 Applications

Metadynamics can explore:

· Conformational transitions in molecules
· Chemical reactions
· Phase transitions
· Protein folding pathways
· Ligand binding/unbinding

It does not require prior knowledge of transition states and can discover new pathways.

