Chapter 23 — QM/MM Methods

23.1 The Need for QM/MM

Large systems (enzymes, materials, solutions) cannot be treated entirely quantum mechanically. QM/MM combines:

· QM region: Small, chemically active region treated with accurate quantum methods (DFT)
· MM region: Large environment treated with classical force fields

23.2 The QM/MM Hamiltonian

\hat{H}_{\text{total}} = \hat{H}_{\text{QM}} + \hat{H}_{\text{MM}} + \hat{H}_{\text{QM/MM}}

QM region: Standard electronic Hamiltonian with modified nuclear charges for boundary atoms.

MM region: Classical force field:

E_{\text{MM}} = \sum_{\text{bonds}} \frac{k_b}{2}(b - b_0)^2 + \sum_{\text{angles}} \frac{k_\theta}{2}(\theta - \theta_0)^2 + \sum_{\text{dihedrals}} k_\phi[1 + \cos(n\phi - \delta)] + \sum_{i<j} \left[ \frac{q_i q_j}{r_{ij}} + 4\epsilon_{ij}\left( \frac{\sigma_{ij}^{12}}{r_{ij}^{12}} - \frac{\sigma_{ij}^6}{r_{ij}^6} \right) \right]

QM/MM coupling:

\hat{H}_{\text{QM/MM}} = \sum_{i \in \text{QM}} \sum_{A \in \text{MM}} \frac{q_A}{|\mathbf{r}_i - \mathbf{R}_A|} + \sum_{B \in \text{QM}} \sum_{A \in \text{MM}} \frac{Z_B q_A}{|\mathbf{R}_B - \mathbf{R}_A|} + E_{\text{vdW}}^{\text{QM-MM}}

The first term (electrostatic embedding) polarizes the QM region by MM point charges.

23.3 Boundary Treatments

When the QM/MM boundary cuts through covalent bonds (e.g., in proteins), special treatments are needed:

· Link atoms: Add hydrogen atoms to saturate QM region
· Localized orbitals: Frozen orbital methods keep the bond orbital in the QM region
· Pseudopotentials: Replace boundary atoms with effective potentials

23.4 Applications

QM/MM is essential for:

· Enzyme catalysis (understanding reaction mechanisms in the protein environment)
· Photobiology (vision, photosynthesis)
· Materials science (defects, surfaces)
· Drug design (ligand binding, reactivity)

