Chapter 26 — Proteins: Structure and Folding

26.1 The Peptide Bond

Proteins are linear polymers of amino acids linked by peptide bonds. Each amino acid consists of a central carbon ($C_\alpha$), an amino group ($-NH_2$), a carboxyl group ($-COOH$), and a side chain ($R$). The peptide bond forms between the carboxyl of one amino acid and the amino of the next:

\text{Amino acid}_1\text{-COO}^- + \text{NH}_3^+\text{-Amino acid}_2 \rightarrow \text{Amino acid}_1\text{-CO-NH-Amino acid}_2 + H_2O

The peptide bond has partial double-bond character due to resonance, making it planar and restricting rotation:

\begin{array}{c}
O \\
|| \\
C_\alpha - C - N - C_\alpha \\
| \quad | \quad | \\
H \quad H
\end{array}

The planarity is quantified by the peptide bond length ($\approx 1.33$ Å, intermediate between C–N single bond ($1.47$ Å) and C=N double bond ($1.27$ Å)).

26.2 Protein Structure Hierarchy

Primary structure: The linear sequence of amino acids. Represented as a string of letters: e.g., Gly-Ala-Val-Leu-... The sequence determines everything else.

Secondary structure: Local hydrogen-bonded patterns.

The $\alpha$-helix: $i \rightarrow i+4$ hydrogen bonds (carbonyl of residue $i$ to amide of residue $i+4$). Parameters: rise per residue $1.5$ Å, $3.6$ residues per turn.

The $\beta$-sheet: Hydrogen bonds between adjacent strands. Parallel or antiparallel.

Ramachandran plot: Maps the dihedral angles $\phi$ (rotation around $N-C_\alpha$ bond) and $\psi$ (rotation around $C_\alpha-C$ bond). Allowed regions correspond to sterically favorable conformations (α-helix, β-sheet, left-handed helix).

Tertiary structure: Three-dimensional folding of a single polypeptide chain. Stabilized by:

· Hydrophobic effect: nonpolar side chains cluster interior
· Hydrogen bonds: between side chains and backbone
· Ionic interactions: salt bridges
· Disulfide bonds: covalent S–S links between cysteine residues

Quaternary structure: Assembly of multiple polypeptide subunits.

26.3 The Protein Folding Problem

Given the primary sequence, can we predict the tertiary structure? This is the protein folding problem.

Levinthal's paradox: If a protein searched all possible conformations randomly, it would take astronomical time. Yet proteins fold in milliseconds to microseconds. Therefore, folding is not random—there is a folding pathway.

Energy landscape theory: The folding landscape is funnel-shaped, with many high-energy unfolded states and a single low-energy native state. The funnel slope guides the protein toward the native structure.

The free energy of folding is:

\Delta G_{\text{fold}} = G_{\text{native}} - G_{\text{unfolded}}

Stable proteins have $\Delta G_{\text{fold}} < 0$, typically $-5$ to $-15$ kcal/mol.

26.4 The Folding Funnel

The energy landscape can be described by a few coordinates (reaction coordinates). The potential of mean force (PMF) along coordinate $Q$ (fraction of native contacts) is:

F(Q) = -k_B T \ln P(Q)

where $P(Q)$ is the probability distribution from simulations.

The folding rate depends on the barrier height $\Delta F^\ddagger$ between unfolded and native states:

k_f = k_0 e^{-\Delta F^\ddagger / k_B T}

26.5 Predicting Protein Structure

Modern methods (AlphaFold2) use deep learning to predict structures from sequences. They leverage co-evolutionary information: if two residues mutate together, they are likely close in space. The AlphaFold2 loss function includes:

\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{distogram}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{angle}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{TM-score}}

where the distogram predicts distances between residues, and angles predict backbone geometry.

26.6 Protein Dynamics

Proteins are not static; they fluctuate around their native structure. Normal modes analysis (NMA) solves:

M \ddot{\mathbf{q}} = -H \mathbf{q}

where $H$ is the Hessian of the potential energy. The low-frequency modes correspond to collective motions (hinge bending, shear motions) relevant to function.

