Chapter 27 — Nucleic Acids: Information Storage

27.1 DNA and RNA Structure

Nucleic acids are polymers of nucleotides. Each nucleotide consists of:

· A phosphate group ($-PO_4^{2-}$)
· A sugar (deoxyribose in DNA, ribose in RNA)
· A nitrogenous base (purine: adenine, guanine; pyrimidine: cytosine, thymine (DNA), uracil (RNA))

The backbone is sugar-phosphate-sugar-phosphate, with bases attached to the sugars.

Watson-Crick base pairing:

· A–T (or A–U in RNA): two hydrogen bonds
· G–C: three hydrogen bonds

Base pairing energy (per mol) from hydrogen bonds and stacking interactions:

\Delta G_{\text{base pair}} \approx -1 \text{ to } -3 \text{ kcal/mol}

27.2 Double Helix Geometry

The B-form DNA helix has:

· Diameter: 20 Å
· Rise per base pair: 3.4 Å
· Twist per base pair: 36° (10.5 bp per turn)
· Major groove: wide, accessible
· Minor groove: narrow

27.3 Thermodynamics of Hybridization

The stability of a DNA duplex is given by the melting temperature $T_m$, where half the strands are dissociated. Nearest-neighbor models sum contributions from each pair of adjacent base pairs:

\Delta G^\circ_{\text{total}} = \sum \Delta G^\circ(\text{neighbors}) + \Delta G^\circ_{\text{init}}

The melting temperature is:

T_m = \frac{\Delta H^\circ}{\Delta S^\circ + R \ln(C_t / 4)}

for self-complementary strands, where $C_t$ is total strand concentration.

27.4 DNA as Information Storage

The genetic code maps triplets of bases (codons) to amino acids. The information content per base is 2 bits (since 4 bases). The human genome ($\approx 3 \times 10^9$ bp) contains $\approx 6 \times 10^9$ bits of information.

The central dogma:

\text{DNA} \xrightarrow{\text{transcription}} \text{RNA} \xrightarrow{\text{translation}} \text{Protein}

Transcription: RNA polymerase synthesizes RNA complementary to DNA template.

Translation: Ribosome reads mRNA codons, assembles amino acids via tRNA adapters.

27.5 DNA-Protein Interactions

Proteins recognize specific DNA sequences through:

· Hydrogen bonds with base edges (in major groove)
· Shape complementarity
· Electrostatic interactions with backbone

Binding free energy:

\Delta G_{\text{bind}} = \Delta G_{\text{electrostatic}} + \Delta G_{\text{hydrophobic}} + \Delta G_{\text{conf}}

Typical specific binding: $\Delta G_{\text{bind}} \approx -10$ to $-15$ kcal/mol ($K_d \approx 10^{-8}$ to $10^{-12}$ M).

