Chapter 29 — Metabolism: Networks and Flux

29.1 Metabolic Pathways

Metabolism is the sum of all chemical reactions in a cell. Pathways are sequences of enzyme-catalyzed steps converting substrates to products.

Examples:

· Glycolysis: glucose → pyruvate (10 steps)
· Citric acid cycle: acetyl-CoA → CO₂ (8 steps)
· Electron transport chain: NADH → ATP via proton gradient

29.2 Stoichiometric Matrix

A metabolic network can be represented by the stoichiometric matrix $S$, where $S_{ij}$ is the stoichiometric coefficient of metabolite $i$ in reaction $j$. At steady state, fluxes $v_j$ satisfy:

S \cdot \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}

This is a linear system. The null space of $S$ contains all steady-state flux distributions.

29.3 Flux Balance Analysis (FBA)

FBA maximizes an objective function (e.g., biomass production) subject to constraints:

\begin{aligned}
\text{maximize} & \quad \mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{v} \\
\text{subject to} & \quad S \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0} \\
& \quad \mathbf{v}_{\text{min}} \le \mathbf{v} \le \mathbf{v}_{\text{max}}
\end{aligned}

where $\mathbf{c}$ is the objective vector. FBA predicts growth rates and flux distributions in microorganisms.

29.4 Thermodynamic Constraints

Flux direction is constrained by Gibbs free energy:

\Delta G = \Delta G^{\circ'} + RT \ln Q

where $Q$ is the mass-action ratio. For a reaction to proceed forward, $\Delta G < 0$.

The equilibrium constant relates to standard free energy:

K = e^{-\Delta G^{\circ'}/RT}

29.5 Metabolic Control Analysis

Metabolic Control Analysis (MCA) quantifies how fluxes are controlled by enzymes. Control coefficients:

· Flux control coefficient: $C_{E_i}^J = \frac{\partial \ln J}{\partial \ln [E_i]}$
· Concentration control coefficient: $C_{E_i}^{S_j} = \frac{\partial \ln [S_j]}{\partial \ln [E_i]}$

Summation theorems:

\sum_i C_{E_i}^J = 1, \quad \sum_i C_{E_i}^{S_j} = 0

29.6 The Cell as a Chemical Computer

Metabolism can be viewed as computation: substrates are inputs, products are outputs, enzymes are logic gates, pathways are circuits.

The metabolic network is a directed graph. Fluxes are determined by:

· Enzyme kinetics (rate laws)
· Substrate availability
· Allosteric regulation
· Thermodynamic constraints

This perspective connects chemistry to information processing.

