Chapter 33 — Semiconductors and Doping

33.1 Intrinsic Semiconductors

At $T=0$, intrinsic semiconductors have fully occupied valence band, empty conduction band. At finite $T$, thermal excitation creates electron-hole pairs.

The carrier concentration is:

n = p = N_c N_v e^{-E_g / 2k_B T}

where $N_c = 2\left( \frac{2\pi m_e^* k_B T}{h^2} \right)^{3/2}$ is effective density of states in conduction band.

33.2 Doping

Adding impurities creates extrinsic semiconductors:

· n-type: Donor atoms (Group V in Si: P, As) add extra electrons
· p-type: Acceptor atoms (Group III in Si: B, Al) create holes

At room temperature, dopants are ionized, giving carrier concentrations:

n \approx N_d \quad (\text{n-type}), \quad p \approx N_a \quad (\text{p-type})

33.3 Fermi Level

The Fermi level shifts with doping. For n-type:

E_F = E_c - k_B T \ln \frac{N_c}{N_d}

For p-type:

E_F = E_v + k_B T \ln \frac{N_v}{N_a}

33.4 p-n Junction

When p and n materials meet, diffusion creates a depletion region with built-in potential:

V_{\text{bi}} = \frac{k_B T}{e} \ln \frac{N_a N_d}{n_i^2}

Under forward bias, current flows exponentially:

I = I_0 \left( e^{eV/k_B T} - 1 \right)

