Chapter 35 — Polymers and Soft Matter

35.1 Polymer Statistics

An ideal polymer chain is a random walk. The end-to-end distance:

\langle R^2 \rangle = N l^2

where $N$ is number of segments, $l$ is segment length. For a real chain with excluded volume (self-avoiding walk):

\langle R^2 \rangle \sim N^{2\nu}, \quad \nu \approx 0.588

35.2 Flory-Huggins Theory

The free energy of mixing a polymer and solvent:

\frac{\Delta F}{k_B T} = \phi \ln \phi + \frac{1}{N}(1-\phi)\ln(1-\phi) + \chi \phi(1-\phi)

where $\phi$ is polymer volume fraction, $N$ degree of polymerization, $\chi$ Flory interaction parameter. Phase separation occurs when $\chi > \chi_c = \frac{1}{2}(1 + 1/\sqrt{N})^2$.

35.3 Glass Transition

Polymers become glassy below $T_g$. The Vogel-Fulcher-Tammann (VFT) equation describes viscosity:

\eta(T) = \eta_0 \exp\left( \frac{B}{T - T_0} \right)

where $T_0$ is Vogel temperature (below $T_g$).

35.4 Viscoelasticity

Polymers exhibit both viscous and elastic behavior. The Maxwell model:

\frac{d\epsilon}{dt} = \frac{\sigma}{\eta} + \frac{1}{E} \frac{d\sigma}{dt}

Stress relaxation modulus $G(t)$ often follows $G(t) \sim t^{-n}$ at intermediate times.

