Appendix E — Derivation of the QTAIM Critical Point Classification

E.1 Critical Points

At a critical point $\mathbf{r}_c$, $\nabla \rho(\mathbf{r}_c) = 0$. The behavior of $\rho$ near $\mathbf{r}_c$ is given by the Taylor expansion:

\rho(\mathbf{r}_c + \delta \mathbf{r}) = \rho(\mathbf{r}_c) + \frac{1}{2} \delta \mathbf{r}^T \mathbf{H} \delta \mathbf{r} + \mathcal{O}(\delta r^3)

where $\mathbf{H}$ is the Hessian matrix of second derivatives.

E.2 Hessian Eigenvalues

Diagonalize $\mathbf{H}$ to obtain eigenvalues $\lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \lambda_3$ and corresponding eigenvectors. The signature $\sigma$ is the sum of the signs of the eigenvalues:

\sigma = \text{sgn}(\lambda_1) + \text{sgn}(\lambda_2) + \text{sgn}(\lambda_3)

E.3 Morse Theory

In Morse theory, critical points of a scalar field are classified by the pair $(\text{rank}, \text{signature})$, where rank is the number of non-zero eigenvalues. For electron density, all eigenvalues are non-zero at non-degenerate critical points, so rank = 3.

Four types of critical points in molecules:

1. Nuclear critical point (NCP): (3, -3) — all eigenvalues negative, local maximum
2. Bond critical point (BCP): (3, -1) — two negative, one positive, saddle
3. Ring critical point (RCP): (3, +1) — one negative, two positive, saddle
4. Cage critical point (CCP): (3, +3) — all eigenvalues positive, local minimum

E.4 Poincaré-Hopf Theorem

The number of each type of critical point is related by the Poincaré-Hopf theorem:

n_{\text{nuclear}} - n_{\text{bond}} + n_{\text{ring}} - n_{\text{cage}} = 1

for a finite molecule. This provides a topological consistency check.

