Appendix G — Derivation of the Michaelis-Menten Equation

G.1 The Reaction Mechanism

Consider the simplest enzyme mechanism:

E + S \underset{k_{-1}}{\overset{k_1}{\rightleftharpoons}} ES \xrightarrow{k_2} E + P

G.2 Rate Equations

The rate of product formation is:

v = \frac{d[P]}{dt} = k_2 [ES]

The rate of change of $[ES]$ is:

\frac{d[ES]}{dt} = k_1 [E][S] - k_{-1}[ES] - k_2[ES]

G.3 Steady-State Approximation

Assume $[ES]$ reaches a steady state quickly: $d[ES]/dt \approx 0$. Then:

k_1 [E][S] = (k_{-1} + k_2)[ES]

Total enzyme concentration $[E]_0 = [E] + [ES]$. Substitute $[E] = [E]_0 - [ES]$:

k_1 ([E]_0 - [ES])[S] = (k_{-1} + k_2)[ES]

Solve for $[ES]$:

[ES] = \frac{k_1 [E]_0 [S]}{k_{-1} + k_2 + k_1 [S]} = \frac{[E]_0 [S]}{K_m + [S]}

where $K_m = \frac{k_{-1} + k_2}{k_1}$ is the Michaelis constant.

G.4 Final Rate Equation

Substitute into $v = k_2[ES]$:

v = \frac{k_2 [E]_0 [S]}{K_m + [S]} = \frac{V_{\max} [S]}{K_m + [S]}

where $V_{\max} = k_2 [E]_0$ is the maximum velocity.

G.5 Limiting Cases

· When $[S] \ll K_m$, $v \approx \frac{V_{\max}}{K_m} [S]$ (first-order)
· When $[S] \gg K_m$, $v \approx V_{\max}$ (zero-order)

