Appendix J — Derivation of the Tight-Binding Model

J.1 Atomic Orbitals as Basis

Start with atomic orbitals $\phi_n(\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R}_A)$ localized on atom $A$. Form Bloch sums:

\psi_{\mathbf{k}}^n(\mathbf{r}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{\mathbf{R}} e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{R}} \phi_n(\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R})

J.2 Secular Equation

Assume only nearest-neighbor interactions. The matrix elements are:

\langle \phi_n(\mathbf{r}) | \hat{H} | \phi_n(\mathbf{r}) \rangle = E_0


\langle \phi_n(\mathbf{r}) | \hat{H} | \phi_n(\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R}_{\text{n.n.}}) \rangle = -\gamma


\langle \phi_n(\mathbf{r}) | \phi_n(\mathbf{r} - \mathbf{R}_{\text{n.n.}}) \rangle = S \quad (\text{overlap, often neglected})

The energy band is given by:

E(\mathbf{k}) = \frac{\langle \psi_{\mathbf{k}} | \hat{H} | \psi_{\mathbf{k}} \rangle}{\langle \psi_{\mathbf{k}} | \psi_{\mathbf{k}} \rangle} \approx E_0 - \beta - \gamma \sum_{\text{n.n.}} e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{R}_{\text{n.n.}}}

where $\beta$ accounts for on-site energy shifts due to crystal field.

J.3 Example: 1D Chain

For a 1D chain with spacing $a$, nearest neighbors at $\pm a$:

E(k) = E_0 - \beta - 2\gamma \cos(ka)

This gives a cosine band of width $4\gamma$.

